long_desc.thetext: Alex could you please have a look. Fabian means that in the past there was a similar problem and you could have some ideas to fix the issue.
lowered importance. Alex, isn't there a similar bug?

I haven't retried this with any later releases of Qooxdoo, so I don't know if this is still an issue. However, if it's still an issue, then the severity is certainly higher than "minor" for anyone trying to use Selectboxes using the Inline DIV method. As I remember, clicking on the Selectbox element causes the positioning error to be corrected, so the fix should be relatively easy. I see that Christian confirmed that the problem exists, but I see no follow-up work to determine why it happens and correct it, so I can only assume that the problem still occurs in the current trunk version - can someone who has the current trunk version downloaded verify that this is still a problem and close the bug if it's been resolved? Otherwise, I'd like to see the severity left as normal rather than being demoted.
Thanks, Gene
(In reply to comment #3) > lowered importance. Alex, isn't there a similar bug? Yes, there is a similar bug concerning positioning for IE browsers -> see Bug #2035

I reviewed Bug #2035 and agree that this issue could be related to the the style position settings as well, but this bug has a subtle difference from Bug #2035 in that it happens on initial rendering and self-corrects when you click on the SelectBox element, rather than being related to resizing actions. It seems opposite of Bug #2035, in that something in the click-response code "heals" the issue, so I think that's an important clue.
I did some recent work on positioning in IE6 with DIV elements outside of Qooxdoo, so I'm quite familiar with the challenges of the position style setting with IE6 (too familiar, some might say). I know that the possible position style values are not fully implemented in IE6, so maybe that has something to do with this issue, but I can't explain why it self-corrects when the SelectBox is focused - that piece of the puzzle seems really strange to me.
Gabriel, please check if thats still valid and get back to me if.
As this is IE6 only, I don't think we get that fixed in the time s long as IE6 is valid.
